'''Amber Merritt''' (born 17 February 1993) is a [[4.5 point player|4.5-point]] [[wheelchair basketball]] player  who plays [[forward (basketball)|forward]]. She represented Australia at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in London, where she won a silver medal.

Born in England, Merritt moved to Australia when she was ten years old. She was originally a swimmer, but was recruited into basketball by the [[Paralympic Hall of Fame]] coach [[Frank Ponta]] in 2007. She started playing top level club wheelchair basketball in Australia for the Perth Western Stars in the [[Women's National Wheelchair Basketball League]] (WNWBL) in 2008.  In 2013, she captained the team, and it to its first WNWBL championship. She was the league's top scorer, and the [[Most Valuable Player]] 4 pointer in its All Star Five, in 2011, 2012 and 2013.

Merritt made her debut with the [[Australia women's national wheelchair basketball team]], known as the Gliders, in 2009. She has played for the Gliders in a number of international series including the 2010 U23 World Championship, 2011 U25 World Championship, 2011, 2012 and 2013 Osaka Cups, the 2012 BT Paralympic World Cup, and 2012 Gliders and Rollers World Challenge in Sydney.

==Personal==
[[File:The interview with four players.ogg|thumb|right|[[:n:Main Page|Wikinews reporters]] interview Australian Gliders [[Leanne Del Toso]], [[Sarah Vinci]], Amber Merritt and [[Clare Nott]]]]
[[File:Aussie Gilder player 8476 04.JPG|thumb|left|upright|alt=wheelchair basketball player|Merritt after taking a free throw at a game in Sydney]]
Nicknamed Bambi, Merritt was born on 17 February 1993 in [[Portsmouth]], England, with a [[club foot]].<ref name=apc/><ref name=sprotingpulse>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/team_info.cgi?action=PSTATS&pID=189767472&client=1-6734-84473-163738-10141848 |title=Player statistics for Amber Merritt |publisher=SportingPulse |date=17 February 1993 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> She moved to [[Perth]] in [[Western Australia]] when she was ten after her parents decided they wanted to see what else the world had to offer, and graduated from high school there in 2010.<ref name=sprotingpulse/> {{As of|2013}}, she lives in [[Wanneroo]], Western Australia.<ref name=apc/><ref name=fromfa>{{cite web|last=Robinson |first=Chris |url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/sport/2022-world-cup-bid/seven-wa-basketballers-picked-for-paralympics/story-e6frg25u-1226418182721 |title=Seven WA basketballers picked for Paralympics |publisher=Perth Now |date=6 July 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref>

==Wheelchair basketball==
Merritt is a [[4.5 point player|4.5-point]] wheelchair basketball who plays [[forward (basketball)|forward]].<ref name=apc>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/team/amber-merritt |title=Amber Merritt |publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee |location=Australia |year=2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=fromwa3>{{cite web|author=Glen Foreman |url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/olympic-games/brad-ness-ready-to-compete-in-fourth-paralympics/story-fn5k3iok-1226419892151 |title=Ness on path to fourth Paralympics |publisher=Fox Sports |date=8 July 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> She started playing in 2007.<ref name=apc/> She was originally a swimmer, but was recruited into basketball by the [[Paralympic Hall of Fame]] coach [[Frank Ponta]].<ref name="Australian women's wheelchair basketball teams beats Mexico">{{cite web |url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/more-sport/australian-womens-wheelchair-basketball-teams-beats-mexico/story-fndukor0-1226465200079 |title=Australian women's wheelchair basketball teams beats Mexico |last=Foreman |first=Glen |date=5 September 2012 |publisher=News Ltd |accessdate=2 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/news/australia%E2%80%99s-greatest-inducted-paralympic-hall-fame |title=Australia's Greatest Inducted into Paralympic Hall of Fame |last=Mannion |first=Tim |date=29 August 2011 |accessdate=14 February 2012 }}</ref>

In [[financial year]] 2012/13, the [[Australian Sports Commission]] gave Merritt a [[Australian dollar|A$]]20,000 grant as part of their Direct Athlete Support (DAS) program. She received $17,000 in 2011/12 and 2010/11 and $5,571.42 in 2009/10.<ref name=aussprtcom>{{cite web|url=https://ausport.gov.au/supporting/funding/grants_and_scholarships/grant_funding_report |title=Grant Funding Report|publisher=Australian Sports Commission|location=Bruce, Australian Capital Territory  |accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref>

Wearing jersey number 14,<ref name=sprotingpulse/> Merritt started playing top level club wheelchair basketball in Australia for the Perth Western Stars in the [[Women's National Wheelchair Basketball League]] in 2008. In the second round of that season, the Western Stars defeated the Hills Hornets 52<U+2013>44. Playing for the Stars, she scored 10 points in her team's victory.<ref name=somethign2008>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-4219-0-0-0&sID=71792&articleID=5482591&news_task=DETAIL |title=WNWBL Round 2 <U+2013> National Wheelchair Basketball League (NWBL) |publisher=SportingPulse |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=perthwesternstars>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketballvictoria.com.au/index.php?id=138 |title=Gliders v Japan |publisher=Basketball Victoria |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=sprotingpulse/><ref name=2012stars>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=11-6734-0-0-0&sID=119018&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=15950198 |title=New-look WNWBL ignites this weekend&nbsp;<U+2014> Women's National Wheelchair Basketball League |publisher=SportingPulse |date=30 June 2012 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref>

In the 2012 season during the first game loss, Merritt scored eight points, had five rebounds, and two assists. In the league's third game and her team's second game, a loss to the Dandenong Rangers, she scored 26 points, and had 14 rebounds. In her team's third game victory against the Sydney Uni Flames, she scored 18 points, while having 10 rebounds.<ref name=2012season>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=11-6734-0-0-0&sID=119018&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=19064669 |title=Bears still on top after Round 3 <U+2013> Women's National Wheelchair Basketball League |publisher=SportingPulse |date=29 June 2012 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> In the Western Stars' 56<U+2013>36 semifinal victory against the Sydney Uni Flames, she played an important role. The Western Stars played in the league's third place match, where she led it in scoring with 34 points as they defeated Sydney 63<U+2013>54.<ref name=2012wnwbl/> She finished the season as the WNWBL Season Top Scorer,<ref name=2012wnwbl>{{cite web|url=http://www.sports.org.au/index.php?option=com_flexicontent&view=items&cid=6&id=269 |title=News <U+2013> 2012 WNWBL Champions |publisher=Athletes with a Disability |date=25 June 2012 |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>

Merritt was the Western Stars' captain for the 2013 season, and led the team to its first WNWBL championship, defeating the Sachs Goldcamp Bears in the final 43<U+2013>40 despite being 11 points down at three-quarter time. She was the league's top scorer, and the [[Most Valuable Player]] 4 pointer in its All Star Five,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wasportsfed.asn.au/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/western-stars.pdf |accessdate=25 September 2013 |publisher=Western Australian Sports Federation |title=Be Active Western Stars Crowned WNWBL Champions in Thrilling Style }}</ref> as she had previously been in 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sports.org.au/athletes-profiles/235-victoria-dandenong-rangers-take-home-2011-wnwbl-trophy |title=Victoria Dandenong Rangers Take Home 2011 WNWBL Trophy |publisher=Disability Sports Australia |accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-6734-0-0-0&sID=119018&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=19770330 |title=Rangers take out WNWBL Championship |publisher=Sporting Pulse |accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref>

Merritt made her debut with the [[Australia women's national wheelchair basketball team]], known as the Gliders, in 2009,<ref name=apc/><ref name=perthwesternstars/> playing in several different competitions that year including the Japan Friendly Series, Four Nations in Canada and the Under 23 World Championship where her team finished fourth.<ref name=sprotingpulse/> As the youngest member of the Australian team at the 2010 World Championships, she finished fourth.<ref name=apc/><ref name=isyoungest>{{cite news|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-sport/team-named-for-womens-wheelchair-worlds-20100616-yefb.html |title=Team named for Women's Wheelchair Worlds |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=16 June 2010 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> She competed in the 2011 Asia Oceania Regional Championships, scoring ten points for her team as the third leading scorer in the final game of a competition where her did not lose a single match.<ref name=undreader>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball.net.au/index.php?id=1593 |title=Basketball Australia : Rollers and Gliders Asia champs wrap |publisher=Basketball.net.au |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=southokorea>{{cite web|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/sport/a/-/basketball/10501153/wheelcats-stars-headline-national-teams/ |title=Wheelcats, Stars headline national teams <U+2013> |publisher=The West Australian |date=19 October 2011 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=warosme20111>{{cite web|url=http://www.insideworldparasport.biz/news/9784-australia-name-wheelchair-basketball-squads-for-london-2012-qualifying-event |title=Australia name wheelchair basketball squads for London 2012 qualifying event &#124; Wheelchair Basketball News |publisher=insideworldparasport.biz |date=28 October 2011 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> That year, she also represented Australia at the 2011 Under 25 World Championships,<ref name=apc/><ref name=yeppersthere>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=1-6734-0-0-0&sID=119018&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=16301816 |title=Aust U25 Women's Wheelchair team depart for Canada&nbsp;<U+2014> Women's National Wheelchair Basketball League |publisher=SportingPulse |date=30 June 2012 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> where she wore shirt number 7 and was a key blocker for her team.<ref name=number7>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-6734-0-0-0&sID=119018&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=16423623 |title=2011 Women's U25 World Wheelchair Basketball Championships&nbsp;<U+2014> Women's National Wheelchair Basketball League |publisher=SportingPulse |date=30 June 30 June 2012 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> Merritt played in the 2011 Osaka Cup,<ref name=sprotingpulse/> and the 2012 BT Paralympic World Cup.<ref name=competedatthing>{{cite web|url=http://opta-widget.eurosport.yahoo.net/24052012/8/photo/australia-amber-merritt.html |title=Australia's Amber Merritt&nbsp;<U+2014> Yahoo! Eurosport |publisher=Opta-widget.eurosport.yahoo.net |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> She competed at the 2012 Gliders and Rollers World Challenge in Sydney, scoring the winning points in the first place match against the Germany women's national wheelchair basketball team,<ref name=sheiswinner>{{cite web|last=Vidler |first=Adam |url=http://express.whereilive.com.au/sport/story/paralympics-aussies-on-a-roll-towards-london/ |title=Paralympics: Aussies on a roll towards London |publisher=Canterbury-Bankstown Express |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> and was named the women's MVP for the competition,<ref name=mvpyay>{{cite web|url=http://www.wheelchairsportswa.org.au/news.html |title=Wheel Chair Sports&nbsp;<U+2014> News |publisher=Wheelchair Sports Western Australia |date=30 March 2012 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> having averaged 17.8 points per game.<ref name=178points>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/comp_info.cgi?c=1-5951-0-227623-0&pool=-1&round=0&a=STATS |title=Competition Statistics for Gliders World Challenge |publisher=SportingPulse |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref>

Merritt was selected to represent Australia at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in wheelchair basketball.<ref name=apc/> The London Games were her first.<ref name=firstgames>{{cite web|url=http://www.insideworldparasport.biz/news/10485-australia-names-its-london-2012-basketball-teams- |title=Australia names London 2012 basketball teams |publisher=Inside World Parasport |date=7 July 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> In the group stage, the [[Australia women's national wheelchair basketball team at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]] posted wins against Brazil,<ref name="Gliders Prevail in Thriller">{{cite web |url=http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-prevail-thriller |title=Gliders Prevail in Thriller |date=30 August 2012 |publisher=[[Australian Paralympic Committee]] |last=Abbott |first=Chris |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> Great Britain,<ref name="Gliders Win Comfortably Against Host">{{cite web |url=http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-win-comfortably-against-host |title=Gliders Win Comfortably Against Host |date=31 August 2012 |publisher=[[Australian Paralympic Committee]] |last=Abbott |first=Chris |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> and the Netherlands,<ref name="Gliders Secure Quarter Final Place">{{cite web |url=http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-secure-quarter-final-place |title=Gliders Secure Quarter-final Place |date=2 September 2012 |publisher=[[Australian Paralympic Committee]] |last=Abbott |first=Chris |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> but lost to the Canada.<ref name="Gliders shocked by Canada">{{cite web |url=http://www.basketball.net.au/index.php?id=302&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=2701&cHash=a1295ff31f |title=Gliders shocked by Canada |date=2 September 2012 |publisher=[[Basketball Australia]] |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> The was enough to advance the Gliders to the quarter-finals, where they beat Mexico.<ref name="Gliders Dominate Mexico">{{cite web |url=http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-dominate-mexico |title=Gliders Dominate Mexico |last=Abbott |first=Chris |date=4 September 2012 |publisher=[[Australian Paralympic Committee]] |accessdate=2 February 2012 }}</ref> The Gliders then defeated the United States by a point to set up a final clash with Germany.<ref name="semi final abc">{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-09-07/gliders-down-champions-to-reach-final/4247772 |title=Gliders down champions to reach final |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=7 September 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}</ref> The Gliders lost 44<U+2013>58, and earned a silver medal.<ref name="Gliders get rolled">{{cite news  |url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/basketball/gliders-get-rolled-for-gold-by-german-muscle-20120908-25kzz.html#ixzz2JZwF7Ntf |title=Gliders get rolled for gold by German muscle |newspaper=[[The Age]] |last=Paxinos|first=Stathi |date=9 September 2013 |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref>

Since the London games, Merritt has participated in the 2013 Osaka Cup,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.basketball.net.au/fileadmin/user_upload/_temp_/2013_Gliders_Osaka_Cup_Player_Profiles_Feb_01.pdf |title=2013 Osaka Cup, Japan, Australian Gliders Player Profiles |publisher=[[Basketball Australia]] |accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref> where the Gliders successfully defended the title they had won in 2008, 2009, 2010 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.basketball.net.au/index.php?id=302&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=2806&cHash=156fce3191 |title=Aussie Gliders 2013 Osaka Cup Champions |date=17 February 2013 |publisher=[[Basketball Australia]] |accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref>
{{clear}}

